# Discourse theme development patterns

## Settings

- Define in `settings.yml` (root). Types: `bool`, `enum`, `list`, `objects`, etc.
- Access in JS: `settings.setting_name` (global, no import).
- Access in `.gjs` templates: `settings.setting_name` directly.
- Admin-facing descriptions: `locales/en.yml` under `theme_metadata.settings.<key>`.

## Localization

- Files: `locales/{locale}.yml`, top key = locale code (`en:`, `ru:`, etc.).
- Theme description: `theme_metadata.description`.
- Setting descriptions: `theme_metadata.settings.<setting_name>`.
- UI strings: top-level keys under the locale, e.g. `en: my_string: "Hello"`.
- In JS: `I18n.t(themePrefix("my_string"))` — `themePrefix` is auto-injected, no import.
- In HBS: `{{theme-i18n "my_string"}}` or `{{i18n (theme-prefix "my_string")}}`.
- In `.gjs`: `{{i18n (themePrefix "my_string")}}`.
- Fallback: incomplete non-English locales fall back to English keys automatically.

## SCSS

- Use `@use "lib/viewport"` at top of file.
- Breakpoints: `@include viewport.until(sm)`, `viewport.until(md)`, `viewport.until(lg)`, `viewport.from(sm)`, etc.
- Never use `@include breakpoint(...)` — blocked by `discourse/no-breakpoint-mixin` Stylelint rule.

## CI workflow

- Reusable workflow: `discourse/.github/.github/workflows/discourse-theme.yml@v1`.
- Jobs: `linting` (ESLint, Stylelint, Prettier, RuboCop, stree), `frontend_tests` (QUnit via `themes:qunit`), `system_tests` (RSpec + Capybara).
- Theme name from `about.json` `"name"` field — used by `themes:qunit` rake task.
- System specs use `upload_theme_or_component` / `upload_theme_component` helpers.

## Common pitfalls

- `breakpoint()` mixin causes Stylelint exit 2 — always use `viewport.until()`.
- Ruby symbols like `:topics:create` are syntax errors — must quote: `:"topics:create"`.
- QUnit timeout (10 min) can happen if theme name in `about.json` doesn't match or test files have import issues.
